If the same user calls the API 100 times per second, how to deal with?

User A: 100 hits per second

User B: Normal usage

If you block all attacks â†’ terrible UX

If you accept all attacks â†’ server crash

ğŸ‘‰ Solution: Each user queues up individually

Rate limits are applied to a single user. If a queue is shared, a large number of requests from one user will block other users. Using a separate queue for each user can achieve traffic isolation and ensure that they do not affect each other.

1ï¸âƒ£ What does this module do? ğŸ‘‰ This module manages and limits the number of concurrent asynchronous tasks per user. It uses a queuing system to control request execution order and concurrency levels.

2ï¸âƒ£ What practical problem does it solve? ğŸ‘‰ It prevents individual users from overwhelming the system with too many requests, which ensures system resources remain available for everyone and maintains overall stability.

3ï¸âƒ£ Why not just use a single shared queue? ğŸ‘‰ Using a single queue would allow one heavy user to bottleneck the entire system. By implementing per-user queues, we achieve traffic isolation, ensuring that one userâ€™s high volume of requests doesn't affect the performance of others.